2. Exploiting Firmware Update Vulnerabilities: Many systems allow firmware updates over the network or via USB. Attackers might exploit vulnerabilities in the firmware update mechanism (like buffer overflow, authentication bypass) to inject malicious code during the update process.

3. Exploiting Firmware Vulnerabilities: Directly exploiting vulnerabilities in the existing BIOS/UEFI firmware (e.g., code execution flaws, privilege escalation) to install malicious firmware components.

4. Bootkit Attacks: Some bootkits target the early boot process, potentially infecting the UEFI firmware to persist across reboots. These can be installed via malicious boot devices (USB, CD) or network boot.

5. Supply Chain Attacks: Compromising the firmware during manufacturing or distribution, so when a system is deployed, it already has malicious firmware.

